England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England"},"nl":{"1255–1275":"1255–1275","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1208–Male":"1208–Overleden","1212–Female":"1212–Overleden","1259":"1259","1212":"1212","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1208":"1208","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"1255–1275":"1255–1275","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1208–Male":"1208–Deceased","1212–Female":"1212–Deceased","1259":"1259","1212":"1212","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1208":"1208","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(southern England, of Norman origin): from a diminutive of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Burdo</i>, for which compare   Burdett  . <i>Burdonus</i> and other derivatives of the Gaulish personal name <i>Burdo</i> (‘mule’) are found in France, where it is rare and the similar French surname may derive instead from Old French <i>bourdon</i> in the sense ‘pilgrim's staff’ (compare   Bourdon   1). The personal name, whether of ancient Germanic or Gaulish origin, does occur in medieval England, but rarely.","habitational name from any of various places called Burdon or Burden. Burden in Yorkshire and Great Burdon in County Durham are named with Old English <i>burh</i> ‘stronghold, fortified place’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’; Burdon in Tyne and Wear is named with Old English <i>b̄re</i> ‘byre’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."],"variants":[{"name":"Burdon","meanings":["English: variant of   Burden  .","Polish: nickname for a troublemaker (see   Burda  )."]},{"name":"Bourdon","meanings":["French:","nickname from Old French <i>bourdon</i>, a word with several meanings, from any or each of which the surname could have arisen: ‘pilgrim's staff’, denoting a pilgrim; ‘bumblebee’, denoting someone thought to resemble the insect in some way; and ‘bagpipes’, denoting a piper or pipe-maker. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin (compare   Burden  ).","habitational name from (Le) Bourdon, the name of several places in various parts of France."]},{"name":"Burdett","meanings":["English (Midlands, of Norman origin): perhaps from an Old French personal name <i>Burdet</i>, a pet form of an unrecorded ancient Germanic name, <i>Burdo</i>, or from Gaulish <i>burdo</i> ‘mule’.","Altered form of French <b>Burdet</b> (see   Burdette  )."]},{"name":"Birden","meanings":["Probably English: variant of   Burden  ."]},{"name":"Burdin","meanings":["English: variant of   Burden  .","French: nickname or metonymic occupational name derived from medieval Latin <i>burdinus</i> ‘mule, hinny’ or, alternatively, from Occitan <i>burdir</i> ‘to sport or amuse oneself’.","French: possibly also a derivative of Old French <i>borde</i> ‘smallholding’ (from Frankish <i>bord</i> ‘plank’), used as a designation for a tenant farmer, or of Old French <i>bo(u)rde</i> ‘lie’, used as a nickname for a liar."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Burden was born in 1255, in Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, her father, John Bourdon I, was 47 and her mother, Luce Wrentford, was 43. She had at least 1 son with Francis Empson. She died in 1275, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1255–1275":"1255–1275","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–1275":"1250–1275","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1259":"1259","1212":"1212","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1208":"1208","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","London, , Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, Eng